Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow looking for relatives among the stars, that is, those that have arisen from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and a brief summary of them can be found on the university website.
The reason for the similar chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in clouds of gas that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if a star is born then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can be used to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of relative stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical abundance from that of its relatives in the cluster.
Modeling results from astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer modeled two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
Over the course of several million years, this object under the influence of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists have added markers to the original gas streams and have found that a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved through rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine the possible regions of formation of such objects.
