Recalling the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed legislation that would protect union organization as a civil right.
&quot;Where there are unions, there are middle class jobs,&quot; says Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Progressive Faction Congress.
This is why I am proud to present the Workers&#39; Empowerment Act, along with the civil rights movement symbol, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal options for discriminating against union organizations as for other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of union opponents
Amending the Labor Relations Act to allow workers who face discrimination for membership in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and receive damages and fines - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
However, this is clearly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis, and the co-sponsors of the bill are proposing is to think back to a very American thought.
Despite the attacks unions have received in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world to accept, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time that is still remembered by millions of Americans, when this country simultaneously defended democracy, free speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country pass a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo&#39;s militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware of the role of workers and their unions in shaping the new Japan, they included text that explicitly recognized that &quot;the workers&#39; right to organize and to bargain and to act collectively is guaranteed.&quot;
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler&#39;s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly read: “The right to form associations to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to prejudice this right will not be legally enforceable; measures aimed at these purposes will be declared illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights that drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included the assurance that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests. &quot;
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country consulted other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize - and to have this union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Everyone now knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions, the unions have miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as it should for us.
Formally recognizing labor rights as human rights - and expanding civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against union organization - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge temporarily blocks a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of a Louisiana law that supporters say will likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
The measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Gov. Bobby Ginadl in June and was set to take effect on September 1, would require abortion doctors to have hospital admission authority within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge&#39;s decision means that for now, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
&quot;Plaintiffs will be allowed to operate legally while continuing to gain authority,&quot; Judge John DeGravels wrote in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision on this law.
Abortion advocates have welcomed the ruling, the latest in a string of rulings against similar measures, saying it will give doctors more time to get hospital powers.
&quot;Today&#39;s ruling ensures that Louisiana women are protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,&quot; said Nancy Northup, president and director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a suspension lawsuit on behalf of three of the five state clinics.
It was not immediately obvious whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who were not plaintiffs in this case and also applied for admission powers.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key pieces of Texas law that would close most of the state&#39;s remaining clinics were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights activists, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admission authority laws impose unnecessary medical restrictions on doctors.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women&#39;s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one physician who performs abortions in Louisiana has admission authority at a hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, that doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission authority were pending.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to?
At least half of the products for each type of product in the assortment of retail chains should be made in Russia, says Oleg Nilov, a State Duma deputy from the Just Russia faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, the newspaper Izvestia writes.
The document will still be detailed in order to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. &lt;...&gt; For the rest of the product groups that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers, &quot;Nilov told the publication.
Together with amendments to the article &quot;On the Basics of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation&quot;, the draft law envisages amending the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of products manufactured in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in retail chains is included in the stimulus package for Russian manufacturers.
Several times more domestic goods will appear on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to Sergei Litvinenko, a lawyer for Nalogovik, a member of the Public Duma, an independent expert center, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive and will lead to growth.
Agricultural producers, farmers and small shops will be in the black.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will rise.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will result in higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be developed faster, and a contribution will be made to GDP growth.
Russia&#39;s dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, though not immediately, &quot;the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break through to the shelves of local stores due to high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, after the imposition of the embargo, this niche has become vacant and one can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now is the &quot;moment of calm&quot;, when the old players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about an increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as an increase in prices for finished products, &quot;- said to AiF.ru the first vice-president of the all-Russian public organization&quot; Russian club of financial directors &quot;, Ph.D. Tamara Kasyanova.
Undoubtedly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow the sector to be assigned to local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper due to subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for a buyer will unfold between companies operating under the same industry laws.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian manufacturers are not able to satisfy 50% of the domestic needs of their compatriots in all respects.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to &quot;hold out&quot; the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that substandard goods will arrive on the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of products made in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied, &quot;the expert adds.
Large retail chains, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers, will feel the negative effect of the introduction of quotas.
It is logical that in this situation foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers as well.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported counterparts, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter, as for a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was revived by economists in February this year due to the ongoing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is intended to oblige retailers to reckon with domestic manufacturers when placing orders with suppliers.
Then we will move much faster and more confidently along the path of import substitution, and the production planning system for the required types of products will be created in a shorter time, &quot;says the deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be especially effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is especially high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really capable of completely covering the counters of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can receive a powerful impetus.
As you know, the largest share of imports is kept for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still accounted for by Russian products, &quot;says Kasyanova.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and may speed up this process.
However, this initiative in itself will not lead to import substitution, since this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that a full-fledged import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas; it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees, &quot;the expert says.
Delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean more ovarian cancer kills in rural areas
Angelina Jolie and her brother James posted a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those in urban areas.
Researchers analyzed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent survived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research said those who live in the regions and remote areas of the state are 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who live in urban areas.
SMALL STUDY: New Drugs May Slow Lung Cancer and Ovarian Cancer
Researchers have traced the medical path of women over seven years.
Dr Jordan said the woman&#39;s age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, current medical conditions, and socioeconomic status also influenced the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those with advanced cancer at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
While the study was not intended to determine why women living outside urban areas are more likely to die of ovarian cancer, Dr Jordan suggested that late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in big cities,” she said.
While improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of out-of-home services that allow professionals to treat women closer to home and support programs for people far from home could help.
Dr Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The research, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young Gold Coast mother, Elisha Niv, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
