Inflation is out of vacation.
Will Russians feel the sharp rise in prices?
As a result of cross-sanctions between the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the authorities&#39; forecasts, analysts at VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of the anti-sanctions will lead to an inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year and even less - 6.5%.
However, according to the Kommersant newspaper, this week the Ministry of Economic Development is to make &quot;small but fundamental&quot; adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast up to 2017.
According to the newspaper, the department may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zeroing of income growth.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation were in effect for a year - until August 2015.
How could such a high inflation be expected in such a situation?
The current situation presupposes a one-time shock, but the downward trend in inflation will not change, &quot;a source in the Ministry of Finance told the newspaper.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the financial and economic block of the government regarding inflation and predict a rise in prices in 2014 at the level of 8%.
