By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation imposed &quot;neat sanctions.&quot;
AiF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of FC AForex:
The rise in prices is already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially significant products began to rise in price, the government was forced to launch measures of systemic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unreasonable price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates price increases.
The key factors behind the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal rate of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to population flight into foreign currency, as well as the embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures were kept under control, the cost of a basket of minimum food items would not have jumped 12% in just one quarter.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a supply shock on the domestic market and led to a completely logical increase in the final cost.
Since at the current stage we are unable to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry the risks of an increase in the inflationary component.
If we add here also the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorated prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvaev, director of the analytical department, Alpari
In the 90s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in the 2000s it was also higher than the current level, another thing is that then this was offset by rapid economic growth.
I think by the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, asset manager of MC &quot;Maguta Fund&quot;
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is so far successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector, this may lead to certain difficulties and increase inflationary expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in purchases of hard currency in order to to secure your savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the gradual depreciation of the ruble, both by market methods and by government regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer lull and, perhaps, this fall will become more noticeable.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to withstand, since the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
