Major Chinese companies team up against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China&#39;s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messengers, etc.) and Baidu (China&#39;s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete with Alibaba in the online market.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left even its American rivals eBay and Amazon.com behind, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($ 814 million) in the joint venture, 70% owned by Wanda and 15% by each of the Internet companies, Wanda Group said in a statement.
It is planned to register a company in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine search services Baidu with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a chain of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial properties throughout China and 40 shopping centers.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (over $ 8 billion) to build a movie studio and theme park in Qingdao, a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea.
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $ 960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American cinema chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making it the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by a new competitor Alibaba.
Thanks to the merger, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million to 100 million by next year, according to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company.
The new site should become the world&#39;s largest online-to-offline platform, said Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract online shoppers to come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
&quot;O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce,&quot; said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin (quoted by Bloomberg).
&quot;Now there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation, the chances for everyone are approximately equal,&quot; he said.
China&#39;s e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and according to McKinsey &amp; Co.&#39;s estimates, its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $ 395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg: this is more than the population of any country in the world, with the exception of India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015 this number may grow to 850 million people.
Union of the richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huateng was until recently the richest man in China, but according to the Bloomberg Millionaire Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $ 5.5 billion.
Jack Ma&#39;s fortune is estimated at $ 21.8 billion, of which $ 11 billion comes from his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Li is now China&#39;s third richest man, while Wanda&#39;s Wang Jianlin is ranked fourth.
&quot;This battle is very interesting to watch: the three richest people join forces to challenge the even richer,&quot; Cao Lei, director of China&#39;s e-commerce research center in Hangzhou, told Bloomberg.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after creation: &quot;Rome cannot be built overnight.&quot;
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies, but also for the well-deserved leaders of the global Internet commerce, is evidenced by the report on financial performance of Alibaba for the last quarter published the day before.
Alibaba is often described as a cross between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company made more money than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba&#39;s net profit for the period almost doubled that of competitors - it almost tripled year-on-year to $ 1.99 billion.
&quot;Alibaba still has tremendous potential for generating money, thanks in large part to its mobile applications,&quot; an analyst with Hong Kong-based Arete Research Service commented to Bloomberg on the report.
According to the updated prospectus of Alibaba on the website of the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company&#39;s services in July was 188 million, significantly exceeding the March figure of 163 million people.
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions for the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba is to name its share price ahead of its IPO.
According to the average valuation of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $ 187 billion after the sale of the shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba may debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) as early as September 16.
The company&#39;s road-show leading up to this event kicks off on September 3.
Alibaba&#39;s IPO is expected to be a record in NYSE history and will allow the company to raise about $ 20 billion.
Until now, the record for the volume of funds raised on the US stock exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 carried out an initial public offering of its shares, earning $ 17.9 billion on this.
