The first day of spring is marked by wet and windy conditions affecting flights at Adelaide Airport
SPRING has prepared a chilly surprise in southern South Australia with heavy rains and high winds that have impacted Adelaide Airport flights.
Another 5 mm of rain fell on the city in the evening at 9 pm, following 6.6 mm, which fell on Sunday night.
The last rain was preceded by a couple of short showers with gusty winds, including a thunderstorm that started just before 8pm and poured out almost 4mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter kicked off an early squeeze of spring last week, temperatures dropped again on Monday to a high of just 15.8C in the city.
The squalling conditions are believed to have contributed to the delayed landing of Virgin Airlines&#39; flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was supposed to land on schedule just after 7:30 pm, but was caught in a wind shear zone - a sudden change in wind speed or direction over a short distance - and was forced to climb.
Wind gusts reached 50 km / h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at this time.
Flight data showed that the plane had to climb on a second landing, and the plane eventually landed at around 8:40 pm.
