The calculation of the estimate of construction projects in the Russian Federation will be carried out in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control over the issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connecting to networks.
An expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector has been created under the FAS.
At its meeting, Vadim Solovyov, head of the department for control of housing and communal services, construction and natural resources of the FAS, said that &quot;today&#39;s calculation of the estimate for construction projects is absolutely incomprehensible.
The regulatory framework makes pricing nontransparent and can lead to unreasonable construction costs, according to the FAS.
And they propose to determine the cost of construction of state property at the design stage on the basis of market prices for design solutions instead of the estimated standards and unit prices for technological operations used today.
These proposals have been included in the &quot;road map&quot; and are now being considered by the Ministry of Construction.
&quot;Replacing traditional cost estimates in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry,&quot; Vadim Solovyov explained to RSL.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, therefore sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury &quot;whole tractors&quot; in the documentation.
The Ministry of Construction agrees with the Federal Antimonopoly Service.
&quot;The first developments on the transition to the calculation of the cost of structural elements already exist: methods have been developed for calculating prices for structural solutions, drawing up estimates for these indicators,&quot; Elena Zhukova, head of the department of urban planning and architecture of the Ministry of Construction, told the RSL.
The field of road construction was chosen as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company Profi-Invest Anatoly Demyanko told &quot;RSL&quot;, the estimated standards are outdated long ago, but the business has not yet been offered another mechanism.
“As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, in practice it is difficult to implement, since the construction of buildings often uses completely different technologies,” he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely thanks to government orders.
According to Ekaterina Lezina, Chairman of the Board of the Non-Commercial Partnership &quot;Expert Community of State Order Professionals&quot;, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director for engineering at the Rosatom capital construction industry center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts, and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is maximally protected from someone&#39;s control.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a state order system in such a way that one and the same contractor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion rubles. or several contracts worth more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach must be assessed in terms of the impact on the business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to endow the customer with the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the number of the customer&#39;s staff and budgetary expenses for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer&#39;s specialists will have to have the knowledge to assess the quality of work performed by contractors, as well as their safety.
Often times, such a breakdown will need to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may entail an outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to lack of interest in obtaining a government order for an incomplete volume of work and a small contract amount.
Alexander Yevstashenkov, deputy head of the Procurement Institute&#39;s Expert and Consulting Center, believes that now the state order procedure has turned into a business game for the attentiveness of the contractor.
And he gave the following example: &quot;when filling out the application, the participant must indicate&quot; specific indicators &quot;without specifying the words:&quot; or equivalent &quot;,&quot; must be &quot;,&quot; from &quot;,&quot; more &quot;,&quot; less &quot;,&quot; analogue &quot;,&quot; or &quot;, &quot;type&quot;, &quot;similar type&quot;, &quot;not lower&quot;, &quot;lower&quot;, &quot;higher&quot;, &quot;may&quot;, &quot;may have&quot;, &quot;maybe&quot;, &quot;earlier&quot;, &quot;not earlier&quot;, &quot;not higher&quot;, &quot;not allowed&quot;, etc.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to establish requirements for the content of the application submitted by contractors.
Another problem of 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the participant&#39;s &quot;paper&quot; proposal at the stage of filing an application.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to assess only the qualifications of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, which has not even been started yet, the expert believes.
The quality of work can only be assessed upon acceptance.
The expert council also proposed to move the margin income from the upper to the lower echelon so that intermediate contractors disappear.
The chairman of the expert council, state secretary, deputy head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it will turn out, as in the famous reprise of Arkady Raikin &quot;Atelier&quot;: &quot;Are there any claims to buttons?&quot;
Israeli children return to school after the Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went to school again on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed while the territory was being rebuilt from the fighting.
The start of school brought joy and excitement to the missile-hit settlements in southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, staff at the Pashosh kindergarten, hit by a rocket, removed the traces of debris from the walls and children&#39;s slides before the students arrived.
“We&#39;re a little scared, but we look forward to the future with joy,” said Ronit Barth, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to get back to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was &quot;a little weird&quot; to suddenly start going to school again.
“It was a difficult time and we never left our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the border with Gaza to express his support.
Before the ceasefire ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad stayed outside or fled their homes, moving to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine fragment, questioned whether they should go back.
The Ministry of Education said about a dozen families have still not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools during this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza that was severely damaged by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said: &quot;We will do our best to educate you and ensure your safety.&quot;
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately ended the hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas&#39;s demand to lift the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and to open airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new round of indirect negotiations is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, of whom three quarters were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to Palestinian and UN estimates.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; notwithstanding this, he did not provide substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 missiles and mines at Israeli cities, mainly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
The Israeli attacks damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools, which have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continued, education officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a school in Gaza.
According to the popular criterion, property prices have shown the largest winter growth in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic home value index for home prices in the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
These gains resulted in a cumulative 4.2 percent increase in June, July and August, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
