How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of gold miners and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on 57/1 October Revolution Street (former Bolshaya Kazanskaya) there are 18 apartments.
The house of the 18th century has remained practically unchanged since its construction, except for its dilapidation.
Strangers come here as if on an excursion, and the residents suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is nearly 300 years old.
The old courtyard, the always open door, the creaky staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls are cracked, and in places the street is visible through the gaps from the peeling plaster.
Everything seems to be held on parole.
And the locals assure: &quot;You don&#39;t think this is the case.&quot;
It is very difficult to live in a wooden house of the 18th century, - says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment number 3.
The object is under state protection, but no money has been allocated for its maintenance for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits that the authorities have simply forgotten about.
The last renovation was 40 years ago.
The walls are still holding up at the very least, but the foundation is all rotten.
Many residents still use the toilet outside and wash themselves once a week in a public bath.
How can you be satisfied in such conditions ?!
The road goes right under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only heard before: a stream of cars rushing under the windows.
You see, the glass rattles all the time, we can&#39;t open the windows, but we&#39;re used to the noise.
Man gets used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Moreover, we have two rooms, we live together with our son.
And for other families, conditions are much worse, on the second floor, in general, the ceilings are slightly more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana suggests visiting her neighbor from apartment No. 6, Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman from the doorway offers a cup of coffee and says with a sad smile:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m² for four people, and this is how we live: my husband and I, daughter and granddaughter.
I&#39;ve been here since I was born, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila looks around the room: mezzanine, two sofas with the letter &quot;g&quot;; on one of them is a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very closely and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, &quot;historical&quot;.
But it flows regularly from the ceiling: the plumbing system is no good.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment in an ordinary and surprising way at the same time, like an Italian woman whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it brings together the very old and the recent, the everyday and the legendary:
The plumbing was installed about 40 years ago during the last renovation.
Then they made us a small kitchen in a cubbyhole and a toilet from a former closet.
We live exactly where Demidov and his family lived, servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The Ufa Real Estate Center says that privatization does not matter.
All the same, we will get only a one-room apartment, we cannot pretend for more.
Already four months ago they promised to resettle us, but things did not go further than promises.
I&#39;m not used to complaining and I won&#39;t.
A whole dynasty lived in this apartment (room!): My grandmother and grandfather, mom and dad, me and my husband, and my daughter and granddaughter.
Anything has happened during this time.
For example, hefty rats were running around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are one meter thick!
They say the solution was mixed in the eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house was built thoroughly, thanks to the Demidovs!
Probably, this is the only reason so far no one has been killed by the collapsed ceiling or pile.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house are rotting, the floors have repeatedly collapsed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, like into a well.
They say that it is - under our room there is a secret manhole and a passage to the Belaya River, which was specially made by the Old Believers who once lived here, so that they could hide from danger, if something happened.
They were also pursued.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begged to be allowed to start excavations in the apartment.
And then he tried to persuade them to give them living space in exchange for his one-room apartment on Oktyabrya Avenue.
Lyudmila refused to the historian:
Where are we four in odnushka?
And here there is even a tiny hope that they will give more spacious housing.
If we had agreed to the exchange, we would have won nothing.
However, the Starostin family won nothing.
Lyudmila&#39;s biggest dream is to be resettled, and her daughter and her 16-year-old granddaughter were given a separate room.
That is, a two-room apartment was allocated for two families instead of not the most majestic ruins in which two generations live now.
A pretty, petite girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two cramped rooms with a total area of 23 m², called apartments, her large family lives.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see for yourself what the conditions are.
Plaster falls off in pieces, like window frames, through holes in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms.
The tap water is only cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest building in Ufa, one can be convinced that the Lavrentievs from apartment No. 4 were the luckiest of all.
They occupy the largest rooms on the ground floor.
You are right, there is a lot of space!
The room is 75 squares, three people are registered.
We live in just those rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family, Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One thing is bad - everything around is bursting at the seams, falling apart, falling apart.
The neighbors have probably already told!
Most of all we suffer with the floors: the wooden boards have rotted, the earth literally disappeared from under our feet.
I put up supports, wedges; in the hall there is still nothing, but in the other room we walk like we swing on a swing, everything is so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell about the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov better than any guide.
He treats the gold miner as if he were his own, and speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was outstanding: the owner of the Kaginsky and Uzyansky factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then there were wooden chambers for carriages, stables and guardhouses around, which were later demolished.
In 1968 they wanted to clean our house too, but something got in the way ...
History repeated itself in 2014: again beckoned to new housing.
We, as if on command, collected all the documents, ran around the necessary authorities, and suddenly found out that the move to apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
Something we don&#39;t believe in all this anymore ...
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to learn about the fate of the house.
The officials did not accept the tenant.
They were sent from one table to another, and then, as in a mockery, they gave out a piece of paper without a signature and seal: &quot;The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of tenants.&quot;
I even got the feeling that our house has long been gone in the city plan, because at first it was number 57, then it became 57 A, and now it is 57/1.
As if it had already been demolished in the 70s.
&quot;Russian Planet&quot; appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the land resources department of Ufa, Vladimir Barabash.
The house on 57/1 October Revolution Street is included in the program for the resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I cannot be responsible for the actions of the officials of the 70s, only I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old buildings on October Revolution Street, which are of architectural value, is being successfully implemented.
Residents will soon be resettled in new apartments.
According to Barabash, the Demidov House will be restored by Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
An architectural biennale is currently taking place in Italy, and the Old Ufa project is presented there, among others.
I hope that by 2016 the entire former Old Kazanskaya Street will be restored, the official says.
The houses will get the proper look, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
The Demidov House is likely to become a museum open to everyone.
