4 tips to get the best quality underwater photos and videos
Whether you want to photograph or shoot underwater video, there are a number of equipment options available to you.
The cheapest option is a waterproof soap box like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action camera like the GoPro Hero3 + Silver Edition, both of which sell for around $ 300.
I took these pictures at a family party with several cameras, all for about $ 350.
No matter what equipment you use, there are a few rules to follow in order to get the best results.
Double-check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the camera battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, customize your camera for the type of photos or videos you will be taking.
Some cameras and camcorders have shooting or subject type modes that optimize exposure for dark underwater conditions.
And before jumping into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can sink.
Some cameras are only 5 feet, others 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our buying guide and digital camera ratings for both traditional and waterproof models.
Take a few shots - because many of them will not work.
Point-and-shoot cameras have LCDs to help you compose your shots, whereas action cameras usually don&#39;t.
Even if you have an LCD monitor, it will be difficult to see underwater and framing will be a random process.
So take a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a burst mode that takes multiple shots at slightly different exposure settings, use that.
Stay near the surface.
The amount of light is significantly reduced the deeper you dive into the water.
If possible, stay near the surface when shooting in a pool, river, or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more color in your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Swim closer to your subjects.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but even more important underwater due to the darkened lighting conditions.
Especially important if you&#39;re shooting with an action camera: This equipment is often equipped with a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means you&#39;ll have to get close to your subjects if you want to fill the frame.
