Ministry of Economic Development wants to accelerate the growth of the electric vehicle market
This week, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit to the government a comprehensive plan for the development of environmentally friendly transport in Russia, said Deputy Director of the Department of the Ministry, Oleg Pluzhnikov, at a roundtable held by Vedomosti at the 2014 Moscow Motor Show.
The plan was drawn up on behalf of the government, one of the main goals is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
The document is expected to be adopted in late September - early October, says Pluzhnikov, the proposed measures relate to electric vehicles and hybrids - Russia already has a plan for the development of NGV vehicles.
The plan (a copy is available from Vedomosti) is designed for 2014-2017.
Criteria for evaluating electric and hybrid vehicles are to be developed and how to stimulate the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
A report to the government, which will describe tax and customs measures to support electric transport, will be prepared by December 2014; the concessional lending and concessional leasing scheme will appear by April 2015; and proposals to reduce the price of cars, stimulate localization and create a service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015. it is planned to amend the regulatory legal acts to facilitate the conditions for the construction of charging infrastructure (in parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend to formulate proposals for regional authorities during 2015 so that they also stimulate the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of providing it with advantages in traffic and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such transport.
Finally, by October 2014, the Ministry of Economic Development will include criteria reflecting the effectiveness of supporting the production of environmentally friendly transport and the development of charging infrastructure in the list of indicators for assessing the activities of regional authorities.
The electric vehicle market in Russia is still just emerging - in 2013, about 100 electric vehicles were sold throughout the country.
At the beginning of 2014, the import duty on electric vehicles was zeroed, so sales will amount to about 500 units, predicts Andrey Pankov, chief executive officer of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia.
But even a fivefold growth does not make electric vehicles any noticeable: in 2013, according to the Association of European Businesses, 2.78 million cars and light commercial vehicles were sold in Russia.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric vehicles to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start importing - the company focuses primarily on corporate clients, says Nicolas Remiz, director of strategic planning and partnerships at Renault in Russia.
Most of the other manufacturers of electric vehicles have taken a wait-and-see attitude towards Russia.
Development of electric vehicles is also available from Russian manufacturers - &quot;&quot;, GAZ, &quot;&quot;, but the output is scanty.
For example, in January - July 2014, according to ASM-holding, AvtoVAZ produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low due to the high cost of electric vehicles, admits AvtoVAZ engineering director Sergei Amanov, there will be no breakthrough in this segment without state support ....
The development of the Russian market of electric vehicles, in addition to the high cost of cars (those electric cars that are sold in Russia, are on average twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) are constrained by the underdevelopment of the charging infrastructure (there are only a few refueling stations), says Sergey Tselikov, CEO of Avtostat.
Due to the high cost and low rates of cost reduction, electric cars will remain a niche segment of the Russian market in the next 3-4 years, predicts the editor-in-chief of &quot;Auto Review&quot; Mikhail Podorozhansky, Tselikov agrees with him.
In contrast, automakers say that some EV models are already close to the cost of conventional vehicles.
The Russian electric vehicle market has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that &quot;electric mobility&quot; is real; this, in particular, will be facilitated by the emergence of more and more charging stations, emphasizes the President of the BMW Group in Russia Wolfgang Schlimme.
Such infrastructure projects are being implemented, for example, by the state company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of gas stations are underway with other regions as well.
According to the director of the Rosseti department, Vladimir Sofyin, the company believes in the electric vehicle market and is ready to build gas stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric vehicles in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric vehicles of various brands.
In addition, Rosseti, as a grid company, does not have the right to engage in the sale of electricity; the possibility of doing this with regard to charging electric vehicles is being considered.
Pankov considers the zeroing of customs duties to be the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the electric vehicle market in Russia.
The zero rate will be in effect until the end of 2014, the possibility of extending it, expanding the preferential list is being considered.
Replacing the transport tax with an ecological one (the idea is being discussed and applies to all cars) will also support the market, but not as tangibly as customs preferences, Pankov said.
Transport tax in Russia is low, says Pankov, unlike, for example, Norway, where the tax cut has led to a sharp increase in sales of electric vehicles - now they account for 12% of the market.
Russia also needs incentive measures for car owners, for example, free parking in the city center (as already done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the ability to move electric vehicles along dedicated lanes, which is not yet available in Russia.
