A genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
The British reported that she spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karin Rogers spent most of her adolescence thinking she had only a few more years to live after being diagnosed with another medical condition.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
Charitable organization CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, unsteady gait and tucked toes.
People who are sick may feel numbness or pain and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich&#39;s ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and die before she was 30.
A mother of two, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn&#39;t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me longer to complete.
I could never roller-skate or skate with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical file when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where I shouldn&#39;t, and so I didn&#39;t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in return, I was shocked and experienced the worst panic possible.
I thought that I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that interval.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, &quot;My dear, I don&#39;t think you have this disease because you would already be in a wheelchair.&quot;
I think you have something that poses a much lower threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was diagnosed with CMT.
“When he explained what CMT was, I thought I was drawing out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK CMT charity has announced CMT Awareness Month to try to raise awareness of the disease.
Tax Burden on Washington Zone Entrepreneurs Grows As Economy Recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose moderately last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to new research released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no different.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $ 27.6 billion to state and local coffers in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $ 26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on businesses across the state and locally increased 4.3 percent last year to $ 671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, in its third straight year of growth after successive years in which bills decreased in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study by professional services firm Ernst &amp; Young and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county&#39;s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland&#39;s tax revenue comes from businesses.
Virginia, at 28 percent, brings in the least tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the rise in tax revenue is fueled by a return to former property values of companies, the researchers say, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of less than 1 percent growth.
While a large proportion of these revenues come from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it appears that the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $ 10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $ 9.6 billion more than in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return on property value does not have any similar effect on state and local tax revenue growth in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Virginia and District of Columbia companies pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
&quot;What&#39;s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around DC, is owned either by the government or a non-profit organization that does not pay property taxes,&quot; said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Tax Center.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent rise in business tax revenues cannot be fully explained by the recovery in the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs&#39; incomes also appear to be on the mend, according to this data.
Companies in the region reported state corporate income taxes of $ 2.3 billion, $ 2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $ 1 billion in corporate income tax revenues, the most in the region.
Although the trends are in the same direction, the tax burden on local entrepreneurs does not increase at the same rate in all three localities.
Growth in the District of Columbia was in line with the national average of 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was substantially faster at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a below-average rise in tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) at 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the US Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower state and local taxes for entrepreneurs and an overall better business tax climate than Maryland.
The district was not assessed in this study.
Despite its edge, Virginia is facing competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets for next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3 percent by 2017.
In the meantime, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be doing better and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Business taxes paid in the form of personal income tax by small business owners - the transition structure that most small businesses are structured around - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $ 2.4 billion, at a much faster rate of growth. than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments growing 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014. compared with the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind as lower federal spending affects the region&#39;s labor market.
