Deputies proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians will not be able to be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
A draft law has been submitted to the State Duma, providing for the postponement of the entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is included in the legislative base of the lower house.
Its authors were State Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Fair Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (Communist Party of the Russian Federation).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a faster and more efficient provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the safety of personal data and observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is rushed by parliamentarians, obliges to store personal data of Russians processed via the Internet on the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and retrieve personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indicate information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called &quot;black lists&quot; of violating sites - an automated information system &quot;Register of violators of the rights of subjects of personal data.&quot;
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoy and Vadim Dengin from the Liberal Democratic Party and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma committee on information policy, Leonid Levin, said that he sees no problems in postponing the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storage of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, &quot;from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to lease their servers. and already provides its servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies, which today already provide their servers. &quot;
