Tricky Ways to Save Money on University Textbooks
With university textbooks costing more than $ 1,000 a year for many students, Matt Schroeder, who will soon be entering his sophomore year, has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He devised a system for how to borrow books from undergraduates, offering them nominal compensation to delay selling them.
“I got my $ 180 math textbook for a semester for $ 10 and a Chick-fil-A cookie,” says Schroeder, 19, who is attending Covenant College in Georgia.
The required literature for the past semester would have cost $ 430, he says.
He spent $ 120.
According to the Council of Colleges, the average student spends more than $ 1,200 a year on textbooks and school supplies, but students have a number of options to cut those costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online shopping and creative ideas like Schroeder&#39;s system.
Renting books is becoming more popular, allowing students to use a book for a semester, and is often significantly less expensive than purchasing one.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, reports that book rentals have doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores were rented during the past spring semester, said Trevor Meyer, vice president of Nibo.
Less than half of all books are purchased from university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here&#39;s an introductory course on the best ways to get a great deal.
Purchase in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one-third of what you see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of Mathematical Analysis by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards, and Robert Hostetler costs about $ 290 list price, but a new copy can be purchased for $ 239.99 from Chegg.com, which specializes in textbook sales.
Buying used
If you don&#39;t mind other people&#39;s marks or damage, secondhand textbooks are a good option.
Mathematical Analysis sells for $ 93.49 pre-owned on Chegg.com.
Matt Kasaday, 25, a fourth year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a second-hand copy of Strategic Media Decisions: Understanding the Business of the Advertising Business.
The book sold for $ 48 new.
Educators such as Ingrid Bracey, director of College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, invite students to check with their professors to see if they can use previous editions.
Sometimes updates are irrelevant to the class.
In such cases, older editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the cost of the latest edition.
Besides Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative for buying used books.
Rental
Renting textbooks is worth considering if you are good enough with them, remember to return them, and do not want to keep them for yourself after the course is over.
You can save over 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent Math Analysis for a semester for about $ 20.
Find out the rules of the store where you borrow the books, including any fines you may be charged for marks, underlining, and damage.
If you rent a book, remember that if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes these books are actually rented by purchasing an electronic license for a specified period from distributors such as Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes &amp; Noble Inc.
Renting Math Analysis from Chegg.com for six months will cost you about $ 61.
Bracey says literature students can often find the best prices because many classics are now free to download, while science and engineering literature can be quite expensive.
In spite of everything, look around.
Joe Gault, 29, who is about to start his studies at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using the ISBN number to find out the prices of the book, as this will ensure that you are looking for the exact text you want.
Before ordering online, Gault says, be sure to check to see if the book is actually in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
The delivery of the book he purchased was delayed by four weeks, and in the end he paid full price at the university bookstore.
