&quot;Europrotokol&quot; instead of the traffic police certificate
Casco payments can be received without a traffic police certificate - this is how the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the &quot;Europrotocol&quot; in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft directive, according to which from September 1 this year, in order to receive hull insurance payments, an insured motorist will be able to do without a traffic police certificate.
This, however, is only about those cases when the accident was registered according to the &quot;European protocol&quot; without the participation of the traffic police.
That is, if only two cars were involved in an accident, there are no physically injured persons, the damage does not exceed the established limit, and both drivers have reached an agreement on who is the culprit of the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the &quot;Europrotocol&quot; is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions, it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The bottom line is that often, even with minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be issued according to the &quot;European protocol&quot;, the drivers who have been involved in the accident call the traffic police.
Indeed, in the presence of a comprehensive insurance policy, it was impossible to receive a refund on it without a certificate from the traffic police.
The parameters specified in the draft directive are precisely designed to remove this obstacle to the implementation of the &quot;Europrotocol&quot; in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment for comprehensive insurance in connection with an accident, issued without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit for the &quot;Europrotocol&quot;.
But at the same time, it cannot be higher than the limit specified in the Casco insurance contract.
The idea is, of course, useful and theoretically capable of unloading both traffic police officers and the roads.
