The problem, the DIA explains, is that the clients of a small bank who have bought such a certificate, in the event of their license revocation, are trying to get money from the DIA.
Some depositors who do not have sufficient financial literacy and buy bearer savings certificates may assume that their investments are insured.
Reasonable lack of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of the bank&#39;s license may lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the agency&#39;s practice, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the courts, &quot;the DIA said.
The problem, of course, is far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, since, according to the law, they have no right to compensation from the state.
If the matter was that the instrument was not insured in the DIA, metal accounts on which citizens&#39; funds are accounted for in grams of one of four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium - would be banned along with it.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, however, no one encroaches on their existence so far.
The point is most likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be a registered security, which must be kept in a depository.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right to early redemption.
That is, an analogue of an irrevocable deposit is being introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
