Sinful boredom
Sin City 2: A Dame to Kill For by Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez has revolutionized what one might expect.
The first &quot;Sin City&quot; (2005), filmed with minimal but symbolic involvement of Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between cinema, comics and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it destroys the chain &quot;thesis - antithesis - synthesis&quot;, which is fundamental for modern thinking (if we mean the universe of noir by the thesis, and the cosmos of comics by the antithesis).
Henceforth it should be read: &quot;thesis - antithesis - chaos&quot;.
Sin City 2 is chaotic both on a dramatic and philosophical level: both times it is chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the heroes are familiar from the first &quot;City&quot;, although, behold, the thug Marv (Mickey Rourke), I remember, ended his life in the electric chair, and here, nothing, only manages to snatch - in the role of a kind of people&#39;s vigilante - knives from the air and other axes with strangleholds.
But the old people are literally pushed aside by the newcomers, as if bursting into the city from some other film, the meaning and plot of which the audience is asked not to worry about.
So, the super-lucky player Johnny (Joseph Gordon-Levitt) has its own story, shamelessly cut short by the authors at the most interesting place.
The lustful frigid Eva Lord (Eva Green) and Dwight (Josh Brolin), who take revenge on her, have their own.
But this confusion, in which Dwight, say, cannot be distinguished from Johnny&#39;s face - especially since the faces, like other parts of the body, are demolished to the characters with inexorable regularity - is not a problem and not even half the trouble.
Well these are not people, we understand that these are noir archetypes: a fatal bitch, an overly confident gambler, a detective who has fallen into the &quot;honey trap&quot; of sex, a corrupt ghoul senator.
Well, when the archetype waltzes with the archetype and the archetype drives, then this is no longer a movie, but read that abstract painting.
And asking abstract painting questions about the logic of the plot is simply ridiculous.
Plus, even in this hectic world, there is something permanent.
The battle whores from the first &quot;City&quot; still hold a perimeter defense against the forces of darkness besieging their native slums.
Yes, and the ghost of Detective Hartigan no, no, yes, and look at the light, and Bruce Willis is always nice to look at.
The main problem of Sin City 2 is different.
Frank Miller was good at combining comics and noir as a draftsman, and as a director, he turned the idea of how to transfer comics to the screen.
Comics and noir are two aggressively opposing &quot;realities&quot;.
The comic book phenomenon in its modern form was born in the late 1920s, at the same time when Dashil Hammett&#39;s novels &quot;Bloody Harvest&quot; (1929), &quot;The Maltese Falcon&quot; (1930) and &quot;Glass Key&quot; (1931) created canon noir, then called hard -boiled school - &quot;cool school&quot;.
Or pulp fiction.
Comics gave Hollywood many dozens of heroes: from Popeye the sailor - a spinach eater that gives him heroic strength, Superman, Batman and detective Dick Tracy to the Hulk, Thor, Spider-Man and other &quot;avengers&quot;.
But in any movie based on comics there was something flawed: the drawn characters stubbornly did not want to become overgrown with screen flesh, remained pretenders in the &quot;real&quot; world around them willy-nilly.
Simply put, they were completely devoid of &quot;existence.&quot;
Noir, on the other hand, is the most existential genre of world literature.
After the world wars, the traditional romance - with experiences, characters, family scandals and a historical background - lost all credibility.
What Forsytes, what Thibault and Rougon-Maccara, what even Bolkonsky and Rostovs are generally conceivable after Verdun, Auschwitz and Hiroshima?
Such a novel peacefully mutated into a soap opera format, and a criminal - that is, by definition, marginal - novel rose to the level of philosophical prose.
Hammett learned the hard way what it was like to work as an orderly at the front.
He was a communist.
By the way, such pillars of the genre as writers Horace McCoy and Jim Thompson, directors Jules Dassin, Joseph Losey, Edward Dmitrik were at least close to the Communist Party.
Therefore, noir, the archetype of which they set, is, firstly, rude and cynical, and secondly, purely social.
This is almost an American version of socialist realism.
The first &quot;Sin City&quot; was remarkable precisely because it unnaturally, but organically connected comics with noir.
For the first time on the screen, a comic strip came to life, not in the least ashamed of its graphic nature, and did not pretend to be a &quot;real&quot; film.
The gloom of the corrupt world, where the cardinal ordered the murders, and the senator covered the monstrous sadistic son, was quite worthy of Hammett&#39;s pen.
And the picturesque details like the severed heads with which the sadist decorated his nest, the pen of the genius James Ellroy, the author of &quot;The Black Orchid&quot; and the best - that is, declaratively sickening - representative of the neo-noir.
Sin City 2 is not even a retreat, but a surrender of the radical Miller-Rodriguez style to the comics tradition.
Probably, this was largely due to 3D technologies.
When you watch the second &quot;Sin City&quot;, you feel yourself enclosed in a glass ball, inside which snow falls asleep in a toy cesspool.
However, most often it is not snow, but bloody scraps, but by and large, what&#39;s the difference?
Well, there is nothing to say about sociality.
After all, it is possible only when somewhere, here and there, sometimes, albeit on the side of a dirty swamp, there is a normal world where you can return a girl who has gone along a crooked path or, say, tell inconsolable parents that her destroyer has been punished ...
When in the city of sin there is no place for anything but sin, then sin is no longer a sin, but a norm.
Boring, like any norm.
The chaos of Sin City 2 is just boring.
For the sake of justice, the domestic rental gave this insipid sin a little, but peppercorn.
The credits warn: the film contains harmful smoking scenes.
In relation to the spectacle, in the very vegetarian episode of which a person is broken with forceps, it smacks of hellish humor.
Hammett would have liked it.
