Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional human emotion
An angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States have found.
They talked about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The angry facial expression - drawn and dropped eyebrows, thin lips, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and even children who were blind from birth, who have never seen it, make it, notes lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
In a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion arose to effectively handle disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his terms, and he communicates this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmation of their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more often angry and go to assault, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions unfavorable for them on others, and also prefer forceful methods of resolving conflicts over peaceful ones.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a &quot;bargaining emotion&quot;, the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry expression on the face should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force them to agree as soon as possible with its terms to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated faces on a computer, where each of the seven elements of an angry face was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the drooping eyebrows or the protruding chin separately did not make the face angry, the participants in the study unanimously recognized the person depicted with such features as physically stronger.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one&#39;s own strength, forcing one to agree and submit.
A person flares out his nostrils and purses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that puffs up, or a baboon that displays its fangs.
&quot;Anger&quot; is triggered by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing, &quot;said anthropologist John Tubi.
